{
  "doc_id": "2537",
  "text": "[3] Regional observations have noted mesoscale periodicity at around 100 days in temperature and ship-drift velocities [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ] and 130 days in satellite altimetry [CITATION_4] . [CITATION_5] , using 6 years of surface velocity streamfunction data computed by augmenting altimetry with velocities from sequential thermal imagery , distinguished spectral peaks at 115 and 165 days. The periodicity has been ascribed to the frequency at which anticyclones pinch off from the EAC retroflection [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] and the speed at which meanders in the Tasman Front propagate westward and ''break'' against the coast [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . These are local generation processes, whereas Cresswell and Legeckis [1986] contend that ''geopotential ridges'' from north of the EAC propagate toward the south and can significantly affect the eddy formation process. Once formed, the eddies propagate either southwestward into the Tasman Sea or northeastward to coalesce with the main current [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] ].",
